Up for sale or trade I have my Astra A-90 .45 ACP pistol. This is a steel frame gun, hammer fired, made when Astra was their own company and before Star purchased them and quality went way down hill. I have two 9 round factory magazines for the weapon, original box, and all original paperwork. One magazine will come fully loaded. The gun fires great and I have only put 50 rounds through it myself. The rifling is still deep and the inside of the barrel is crisp and clean. The gun fires very accurately with the hard hitting .45 ACP round. Since this model has an alloy frame, the little extra added weight means that you won't feel the recoil hardly at all. The slide itself sits on a rail that runs the full length of the frame, so it will always be held nice and tight without and wobble. I am selling my Marlin 1894S Lever action .41 magnum rifle in 98% condition - one of the very first Marlin 1894S .41 mag made in 1983 for $1,350.00 or best offer-agreeable to me. 
* The wood is perfect, bore as new, the rifle is in suburb condition. An important firearm in 'JM' Marlin's 140 year long history! 
History reports that after Marlin Mfg. observed the overwhelming successes of S&W sales of the Model 58 followed by the Model 57 .41 mag revolvers, Marlin decided in 1983 to test the market by manufacturing only 1,040 1894S in .41 mag.  My Marlin 1894S has a serial number beginning "17...." indicating it was made in 1983, very unique!  The historical Marlin serial number records reports state that Marlin made only 1,040 of these rifles between "1984 and 1985". This one was clearly one of the very first made, actually made in 1983. It still looks like it just came out of the box. 
Beginning in 1988 Marlin decided to re-introduce the 1894S in .41 mag. and manufactured only 2,573. There are less than 4,000 1894S .41 mag ever made, "JM" stamped of course. In 2003 Marlin made a limited run of 1894FG .41 mag lever actiion rifles with a pistol grip stock. 
* The model 1894S, just like mine, is presently posted by Cabelas Gun Library site for $1,899.00 ( Cabelas Library Stock # 8047174. Call nearest Cabelas to confirm ). 

* Also, GunBroker #430737496 which is a 1894FG, the newer less sought after .41 mag., just sold on 8/03 after 13 seperate bidders bid 23 times for $1,325.00. 

Now is the time to open up the gun safe and take a look at the firearms that have been 'collecting dust and NOT having appreciated in value' and getting them sold and put your hard earned money into a firearm like mine that will reep significant future increases in value. The chances of finding a '1983 Marlin 1894S' in mint condition are near to impossible and will become even more unlikely in months & years to follow. (Cabelas 1894S has the original box so if you're inclined to spend $450.00 more for the cardboard box you will want to contact them before that one gets snapped up.) 
I will ship FFL to FFL only after my FFL Dealer Gun Store has received a USPS check or cash for the rifle, plus app. 20.00 shipping with Insurance. (A Marlin scope rail was mounted using the Marlin drilled and tapped standard receiver holes and I have the original Marlin screws that go with the rifle should the buyer decide to remove the scope mount. I never used this rifle with a scope or fired it.  No holes were ever made in any part of this rifle post mfg.

title: For Sale:  Italian Vetterli (pre-WW1 conversion)
postcontent: Here is a unique piece of Italian Military History.  This rifle was originally designed in 1870, as a bolt action, single shot 10.35X47R cartridge, and in 1887 it was converted to a repeating rifle by adding a magazine.  When WW1 came around the Italians couldn't produce enough Carcanos, so they again converted the Vetterli rifles to utilize the Carcano magazine and shoot the 6.5mm Carcano.  This rifle is in good condition considering its age and has 50% blueing, with minimal discoloration and no major rust or pitting.  The stock has handling marks befitting of a 130 year old rifle but is in good overall condition with a minor crack near the bolt.  This rifle is fully functional and could be a shooter although I think is is more befitting of being a collection gun.  All serial numbers match and this is the original 1870 stock converted with an original 10.35mm barrel sleeved to a 6.5mm bore.  If you are interested in owning this curious piece of history call or text Matt at REDACTED.

title: For Sale:  Utah CFP and Oregon CHL Concealed Carry Class 8/8/2014
postcontent:
Utah CFP Oregon CHL Concealed Carry Class
Firiday, August 8, 2014 7:00 PM
Silver Dragon Martial Arts, 7881 SW Cirrus Dr Bldg 25D, Beaverton, OR 97008
Class registration is $65. Save $5 by pre-registering online!
Pre-Register Online: http://www.keepcalmandcarry.net/utah-cfp-oregon-chl-concealed-carry-class-8-8-2014-Registration

This class covers everything you need to get your Oregon Concealed Handgun License and your Utah Concealed Firearms Permit.

Our course exceeds all firearms safety training exceeds the requirements to obtain your Utah CFP, pursuant to Utah Code Title 53 Chapter 5 Section 704, and your Oregon CHL pursuant to ORS 166.291(f)(G).

Our process starts with issuing you a packet of information, an application for your permit, and fingerprint cards that you will need. We will do your fingerprinting, take your passport photo and make copies of your driver's license before class starts. We do this so that upon completion of this class, you will have a complete packet which you can submit to Utah BCI (Bureau of Criminal Identification) with your payment. You will also have all the information you need to obtain your Oregon CHL from your local Sheriff's department.

Subjects covered are: Basic Handgun Safety, Tactical Issues, Concealed Carry Firearm selection tips, Ammunition, Holsters, Gun Free Zones, Reciprocity, Cleaning, Storage, Firearm Transport, Justifiable Force, Criminal and Civil liability, How to interact with Law Enforcement, and how to apply for your Permit.

After attending this class you will have a fundamental understanding about handgun safety and the rights and responsibilities and laws associated with the carrying of a concealed Handgun in multiple states.

This is NOT a live firing class. Do NOT bring a firearm with you to the class.

Even though the class time is only scheduled to be 2 1/2 hours long, there will be time for questions and answers after the class.

More Information: http://www.keepcalmandcarry.net/utah-cfp-oregon-chl-concealed-carry-class-8-8-2014-Schedule
Download a Flyer: http://www.keepcalmandcarry.net/ClassFlyer/utah-cfp-oregon-chl-concealed-carry-class-8-8-2014.pdf

If you are interested in just the Oregon Concealed Handgun License class visit http://www.keepcalmandcarry.net/oregon-concealed-handgun-license-class-Training_Class
